What is Middleware in Express.js?
In Express, middleware functions are functions that execute during the request-response cycle. They can:

Run any code (e.g., logging)

Modify req or res objects

End the request-response cycle

Pass control to the next middleware function using next()


const express = require('express');
const app = express();

// ðŸ” Custom Logger Middleware
const logger = (req, res, next) => {
  console.log(`${req.method} ${req.url} - ${new Date().toISOString()}`);
  next(); // pass control to next middleware/route
};

app.use(logger); // apply logger to all routes

app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Home Page');
});

app.listen(8000, () => console.log("Server running on port 8000"));



kuch build in middleware

| Middleware             | Purpose                           |
| ---------------------- | --------------------------------- |
| `express.json()`       | Parses JSON bodies                |
| `express.urlencoded()` | Parses URL-encoded data           |
| `express.static()`     | Serves static files (images, etc) |
